AGI - "The Italian Presidency of the G7 invites to prudence and to an absolute de-escalation. We ask to stop the attack on Rafah, see if we're convincing. We call for de-escalation, prudence." This was said by Foreign Minister Antonio&nbsp;Tajani&nbsp;a Rai News 24 commenting on the Israeli attack of the past hours.&nbsp;Tajani also reassured the fate of Italians in the Islamic Republic: "I'm safe," he added from Capri, where the second day of the G7 of foreign ministers is planned. Tajani, in particular, explained that he had spoken with the Italian ambassador to Tehran, Paola Amadei.&nbsp;
The same appeal was also launched by France. "Paris invites all parties to calm and act moderately," said French Deputy Foreign Minister Jean-Noel Barrot, after the Israeli attack on Isfahan, Iran.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"We must do everything we can to ensure that the parties in the region avoid escalation - declared &nbsp; the President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, at a press point in Finland at the border with Russia with Prime Minister Petteri Orpo -.&nbsp; We witnessed the massive attack with drones and missiles from Iran against Israel. It is absolutely necessary that the region be stable and that all parties exercise moderation from further actions".&nbsp; And China has also announced that "it will oppose &nbsp;any action that further tightens tensions," said the spokesman of the Foreign Ministry Lin Jian.
&nbsp;
On the Israeli response to Iran's attack on its territory said its defense minister, Guido&nbsp;Crosetto, intervened at 'Jewish' on Rai Radio Radio 1. "There are two separate chapters - the minister has explained - on Gaza I think that the Israeli determination is to move forward and also to Rafa and that therefore there is no change of strategy. The idea of extinguishing Hamas and somehow making the Gaza Strip safer continues to be a priority for the Israeli government and I must say shared by all Israeli public opinion. It is not only an attitude of Netanyahu, it is quite widespread - Crosetto concluded - within the Israeli parliament and public opinion". &nbsp;
