isAGI - From today India is going to the polls for one of the most anticipated elections of 2024>, the most imposing in numerical terms ever organized in the world. The vote will last six weeks*, until 1 June, and the final results will be announced a few days later. Nationalist Prime Minister Narendra Modi> hopes to win a third consecutive term, but opposition parties united in a broad coalition warn that Indians are likely to lose many freedom if their Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) will remain in power.
&nbsp;
Under the Modi era, India has become a great economy, with the most sustained growth currently recorded, close to the status of superpower. At the same time, for a decade to this part, India is increasingly polarized in religious terms, transformed by a secular republic to an Hindu nation, with strong splits and tensions with Muslim citizens, almost 200 million, 15% of the population.
<h2>Date and election numbers </h2>
The Indian national elections are a gigantic exercise of democracy and logistics > which takes more than a month to be completed. It is voted during seven electoral days: 19 April, 26 April, 7 May, 13 May, 20 May, 25 May and 1 June. All votes from the 28 states of the country and the eight territories of the Union will be counted and the results will be published on 4 June. With 1.4 billion inhabitants, India and the most populous country in the world >: 969 million of them will vote in this year's elections, more than the populations of the United States, the European Union and Russia put together. In addition to these rights, 13.4 million Indian citizens residing abroad, who had to register in order to vote, then return to India to do so. Electors must be Indian citizens, be at least 18 years old and be registered in the election lists. They must also have a valid identity card for the electorate.
<h2> Who will be elected
With a multi-party majority system, the rightholders will elect the 543 members of the Lok Sabha>, the lower chamber of the Indian Parliament; two more seats will be assigned by the Indian President. To form a majority of government, a single party or coalition needs at least 272 seats; He will later appoint one of his winning candidates as Prime Minister. Lok Sabha Members are elected for a five-year term representing a single electoral constituency and wins the candidate who gets the most votes. There are 131 seats reserved for the deputies of the so-called "caste classified" and "tribù classified". These groups are officially recognized as disadvantaged, which constitute about a quarter of the Indian population. India has also approved a law to assign a third of seats to women, but will not enter into force in these elections.
<h2>Numbers and curiosities of a record-breaking election
The Indian elections are valued as the most expensive in the world, even surpassing US presidential elections. According to the Center for Media Studies in Delhi, in 2019 political parties, candidates and regulators spent up to $8.6 billion and this year it is expected that spending will increase further. From the high peaks of the Himalayas to the remote forests of the central states of India, the votes are expressed electronically in over 1 million polling seats.
&nbsp;
Approximately 15 million voters will be employed, travelling by road, boat, camel, train and helicopter to reach every Indian voter. With its 4,650 meters of altitude, Tashigang, a village in the far north of the state of the Himachal Pradesh, on the border with China, is the highest electoral seat in the world >, when in 2022 its residents elected the state government. More than 2,700 parties will compete for the seats in the Lok Sabha, including six national parties and more than 70 state parties. Each party has a symbol assigned to it by the electoral commission that appears on the boards, helping the dozens of parties to differentiate and making it easier for voters to make their choice in a country where about a quarter of the population is illiterate. The power Bjp symbol is a lotus, while the opposition party is a hand raised with the open palm. The symbol of the Aam Aadmi Party (Aap, Party of Common Man) is a broom, which represents its origins as an anti-corruption street movement.
<div </div
<h2>Modi and its Bjp</h2>
The populist premier Narendra Modi and his Bjp remain extremely popular. According to the last polls, they will be able to secure another five years in power. Modi, 73 years old, was elected Prime Minister for the first time in 2014 with a overwhelming majority, when he focused his campaign on a development and fight against corruption. He is credited with implementing welfare and social reforms. A result that allowed him to be easily reconfirmed for a second term in 2019, with a program this time of openly nationalist mold. Five years ago he obtained the absolute majority, with 303 seats for the Bjp, and a total of 352 for the National Democratic Alliance>, against only 52 for the Party of Congress. Then 67% of the Indians went to vote, marking turnout at the highest polls in the country's history. His victory in the 2024 election would consolidate his position as leader among the most important and longevous of India. Modi and his allies aim to conquer more than 400 seats in the Lok Sabha, so that they can change the Indian Constitution.&nbsp;
<h2> The main rivals of opposition
The main challenger of the Bjp is the Indian National Congress, which ruled the country for most of the 77 years post-independence, but which is now at a stage. In an effort to prevent another victory of Modi, Congress has made an alliance with other opposition leaders, including major regional parties, bringing together 24 political forces. This time, the party in power is faced with a large coalition led by the Congress Party. the Indian National Developmental Inclusive Alliance, or 'India', which campaigns with a platform of "saving democracy".
&nbsp;
The key faces of the opposition are the president of Congress, Mallikarjun Kharge>, and the brothers Rahul and Priyanka Gandhi>, whose father was former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi. The mother, Sonia Gandhi, is a powerful and historic opposition leader, but her campaign was much less intense than in 2019. Next to these, another key figure is the leader of the popular Aam Aadmi party, as well as Prime Minister of Delhi, Arvind Kejriwal. There are also regional heavyweights, such as the Prime Minister of Western Bengal, Mamata Banerjee, of the All India Trinamool Congress, and the Prime Minister of Tamil Nadu of the South, Muthuvel Karunanidhi Stalin, who will compete to block a conquest from Bjp in their respective states where Modi still has to succeed in asserting himself.
&nbsp;
The block 'India' has been plagued by intestine struggles and must still present its candidate to Prime Minister. According to analysts, opposition forces must find a figure that can rival with the popularity and appeal of stars Modi enjoys. In addition, the opposition coalition was put under pressure by an incisive Bjp campaign aimed at weakening its opponents. Several prominent opposition members, including the Prime Minister of Delhi, Kejriwal, were arrested or investigated by state agencies for initiatives reported as policies by their parties. The Congress has frozen its bank accounts by the federal tax authorities and said it was asked to pay $218 million in taxes.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

